[0mBelow is a **single‑file** example that works entirely with plain HTML for the form and PHP for the logic.  
No CSS, no JavaScript, no animations – just a text box where you type an expression (e.g. `2+2`) and hit *Calculate*.  
If the syntax is wrong (e.g. `2+*3`) the page will show “Syntax error”.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <title>Simple Calculator</title>
</head>

<body>
    <!-- The form that posts back to itself -->
    <form method="post" action="">
        <label for="expr">Expression:</label>
        <input type="text" id="expr" name="expr" required autocomplete="off">
        <button type="submit">Calculate</button>
    </form>

<?php
/* ----------  PHP logic – no CSS, no JS ----------
   The script runs only when the form is submitted.
*/
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
    // Grab what the user typed
    $expr = $_POST['expr'];

    /* ---- Basic safety check: allow only digits,
       operators (+ - * /), parentheses and whitespace. ---- */
    if (preg_match('/^[0-9+\-*/().\s]+$/', $expr)) {

        /* ---- Evaluate the expression safely.
           We use eval() inside a try/catch block; any parse error
           will be caught and reported as “Syntax error”. ---- */
        try {
            // The @ suppresses the warning that PHP would normally emit
            // on a syntax error – we’ll check it ourselves.
            $result = @eval('return ' . $expr . ';');

            /* If eval() succeeded, $result will contain the numeric value. */
            if ($result !== false) {
                echo '<p>Result: ' . htmlspecialchars($result) . '</p>';
            } else {
                // eval returned false – treat as syntax error
                echo '<p style="color:red;">Syntax error</p>';
            }
        } catch (Throwable $e) {          // PHP 7+ throws Throwable on parse errors
            echo '<p style="color:red;">Syntax error</p>';
        }

    } else {
        /* The expression contained disallowed characters – syntax error. */
        echo '<p style="color:red;">Syntax error</p>';
    }
}
?>
</body>
</html>
```

### How it works

1. **Form**  
   * `<input type="text">` lets the user type anything they want.  
   * The form posts back to the same file (`action=""`).

2. **PHP logic**  
   * On POST, we pull `$_POST['expr']`.  
   * A regular expression guarantees that only digits, operators, parentheses and spaces are present – this blocks obvious injection attempts.  
   * We then evaluate the string with `eval()`.  
     * If the syntax is correct, `$result` holds the numeric result (e.g., `4`).  
     * If there’s a parse error (`2+*3`, `5/0` etc.), `eval()` returns `false` or throws an exception – we catch that and display “Syntax error”.

3. **Output**  
   * The result is printed inside a `<p>` element; if the syntax was wrong, a red‑text message appears.

> **Security note:** Using `eval()` on user input is dangerous in real applications. For production code you should use a dedicated math parser or library that safely evaluates expressions without executing arbitrary PHP code. This example is intentionally minimal to satisfy the “logic only” requirement.
